<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-18T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-18T17:00:00-05:00" n="226" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d226">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/13332</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HEM1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">House</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-18T22:00:00+00:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 18, 1917, 10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.10 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>For the President:</p>
                        <p>The following is short <hi rend="italic">résumé</hi> of the general
                            political conditions.</p>
                        <p>Russia: <persName corresp="#p_KAF1">Kerensky</persName> and other more
                            responsible officials urge Allies to make an offer of peace, basis no
                            annexations or indemnities. They believe Germany would not accept and
                            this would help to solidify Russia. They do not believe Germany would
                            make separate peace with Russia owing to danger of socialistic
                            infection, but they believe Germany will take Petrograd and near
                            provinces in spring. They claim this would suit German purposes better
                            because demobilization of Russian Army would produce anarchy and total
                            loss stores of supplies. …</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward House</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>